chargeHist.descr: Throw/Discharge Bodily Fluid at Public Safety Worker or Prosecutor

result.execSummary:
The defendant Jalaya S Little was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Throw/Discharge Bodily Fluid at Public Safety Worker or Prosecutor, a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 941.375(2).
  • Criminal Damage to Property, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 943.01(1).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

08:44 AM; Case called for Jury status hearing.  Defendant Jalaya S Little in court, in custody, with attorney Jessica A Klein.   Kevin Michael Osborne appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Court notes a plea questionnaire has been filed and inquires how the matter is proceeding.  Atty. Klein confirms her client is prepared to proceed to plea and sentencing today.  State recites the offer, and notes there is a referral for a criminal damage to property case however, he does not have a read in list for that possible charge.  Atty. Klein confirms the offer.  Court conducts plea colloquy with the defendant.  Defendant enters a plea of no contest to Counts 1 & 2, Court finds defendant guilty of Counts 1 & 2.  Court orders Counts 3-5 dismissed and read in. Court also orders case 22FO130 dismissed and read into this case.  Court will also accept the oral read in from the State for the Criminal Damage to Property charge.  Court will also cancel the jury trial set to begin on 05/24/2022.
